üöô The Ministry of Internal Affairs presented new rules for obtaining a driver's license Ukraine plans to introduce significant changes in driving schools for obtaining a driver's license, the Main Service Center of the Ministry of Internal Affairs announced. The latest technologies will be introduced into the exam process to make them as transparent, accessible and efficient as possible. What are they planning to introduce? Verification and access to the exam class is planned - a person who passes the theoretical exam will enter the exam class, where there will be a camera at the entrance. It will recognize the face of the driver candidate, which will allow the person to be directed to a randomly determined workplace in the Unified State Register of the Ministry of Internal Affairs to pass the theoretical exam. üëâ The theory exam will be held in the examination classroom under the following conditions: - FACE ID identification of the person during the entire examination process; - fixation of the face and screen in case of a negative answer to the exam question; - prevention of remote access to workplaces; - control over the behavior of the person; - video recording of the exam process. üëâ cars in the service centers of the Ministry of Internal Affairs will be equipped with a video recorder with 4 cameras - front, rear, two interior projections, an internal monitor to control the angle and operation of the video recorder, alarm sensors and duplicate pedals. üëâ purchase of vehicles with built-in technical equipment of various categories for the service centers of the Ministry of Internal Affairs. That is, now future drivers do not need to look for trucks, cars with trailers, motorcycles for rent, if they are not in the service center of the Ministry of Internal Affairs. Now all these vehicles will be there, and everyone will be able to pass a practical exam. üìπ In addition, it is planned to bring video web cameras located on workstations in the classroom to the examiner's workplace, which will allow you to control the entire process online.

‚ùóÔ∏èNew money: what banknotes began to be withdrawn from circulation on January 1 National Bank from January 1, 2023 gradually began to withdraw from circulation paper banknotes of 5, 10, 20 and 100 hryvnia samples 2003-2007. They will be replaced by coins of 5 and 10 hryvnia and a new generation of 20 and 100 hryvnia banknotes, the press service of the NBU. Ukrainian banks will not issue such banknotes from cash offices for all types of cash transactions. NBU will stop backing such banknotes to the cash registers of banks. SBU announces first suspicions for shelling of civilian objects in Ukraine: evidence on Russian general and Russian Navy admiral collected SBU investigators collected high-quality evidence base on two representatives of the Russian high command, who are responsible for shelling of civilian objects in Ukraine. One of them is the Commander of the Long-Range Aviation of the Russian Aerospace Forces, Colonel-General Serhii Kobylash. And the other is the former Commander of the Black Sea Fleet of the Russian Federation Admiral Igor Osipov. Both of them were notified of suspicion under two articles of the Criminal Code of Ukraine: ‚ñ™Ô∏è Part 2 of Art. 437 (planning, preparation, outbreak and conduct of aggressive war); ‚ñ™Ô∏è—á. 3 Art. 110 (encroachment on the territorial integrity and inviolability of Ukraine). These are the first suspicions that Ukraine announces specifically for the shelling of civilian objects in Ukraine. The maximum sanction of the articles provides for punishment in the form of life imprisonment. Thus, during the investigation, the SBU investigators found that since the beginning of the full-scale invasion, Serhiy Kobylash has been following the instructions of the highest military and political leadership of Russia to destroy Ukrainian cities. It is on his orders that Russian invaders carry out massive missile attacks on residential buildings, hospitals and critical infrastructure in different regions of Ukraine. To carry out air attacks, the enemy uses strategic missile carriers Tu-160, Tu-95MS, as well as long-range missile carriers-bombers Tu-22M3, armed with cruise missiles of the types X-555, X-101, X-55 and X-22. As for Igor Osipov, according to the investigation, in the period from February 24 to August 10, 2022, the official gave orders to conduct systematic missile strikes from the Black Sea on Ukrainian densely populated areas. üè† How can internally displaced persons apply for a housing subsidy? IDPs can apply for a subsidy for housing and communal services at the place of actual residence, the Ministry of Reintegration reports. In this case, the conclusion of a lease agreement is not required, and the composition of the household is indicated by the applicant in the declaration. üìçIn order to receive a subsidy, IDPs need to apply personally to one of these bodies: ‚ûû authorized official of the executive body of the village, settlement, city council of the relevant territorial community; ‚ûû administrative service center; ‚ûû service center of the Pension Fund of Ukraine. üì≤ You can also apply for the subsidy in electronic form on one of the services: ‚ûû portal "Diia"; ‚ûû web portal of electronic services of the PFU; ‚ûû mobile application of the Pension Fund of Ukraine (available for download on Android and IOS). ü™™ What documents are required to receive a subsidy? ‚úîÔ∏è Application for a subsidy (in the prescribed form); ‚úîÔ∏è Declaration of income and expenses (in the prescribed form); ‚úîÔ∏è Data on household members; ‚úîÔ∏è Passport, taxpayer registration number (RNOKPP); ‚úîÔ∏è Certificate of IDP status. The amount of assistance depends on the cost of housing and communal services used by the family and its income level. At the same time, the housing allowance provided to IDPs is not taken into account in the total income when assigning a housing subsidy. üëâ You can find out whether you have been granted a subsidy and its amount online at the link. ‚è≥9:00 Minute of silence üïØ Military pilot Roman Pasulka died on February 24, 2022 in an air battle with Russian occupiers, defending Kyiv region. He was 22 years old. Roman was born in the village of Raukhivka, Odesa region. In childhood, he moved with his family to Chernihiv region. He studied at Nizhyn school ‚Ññ17. Subsequently, he chose the military path. In 2021, he graduated from the Kharkiv National Air Force University named after Ivan Kozhedub, where he received the qualification of a 3rd class pilot. After graduation, he served in the 40th Tactical Aviation Brigade of the Air Force of the Armed Forces of Ukraine, which is located in Vasylkiv, Kyiv region. He flew on MiG-29 fighter aircraft. On the first day of the full-scale war, Roman defended the Ukrainian sky. He held back the attack of the Russian military, covering his colleagues and protecting civilians. "On February 24, when Russian troops shamefully invaded the territory of Ukraine, Roman received a combat mission and without hesitation took to the skies to defend his homeland. Saving thousands of civilian lives - at the cost of his own life. In the memory of colleagues, Roman will forever remain sincere, smiling, full of many plans for life, which, unfortunately, were not destined to come true. His parents brought Roman up to be a real warrior, strong-willed and courageous patriot of his homeland... Roman was a good student, despite his young age - a professionally trained pilot," - the brigade informed. Senior Lieutenant Pasulka was posthumously awarded the Order "For Courage" of the III degree. The officer was buried in Nizhyn, Chernihiv region. Roman is survived by his parents, sister and beloved girlfriend.

From January 1, all insurance payments are made by the Pension Fund of Ukraine: what it means for citizens Despite the war, the state continues to fulfill its social obligations to Ukrainians, including the provision of state social insurance. The Government has quickly and efficiently implemented the requirements of the Law No. 2620 adopted in September to introduce a new organizational model of social insurance in Ukraine. Despite the change of the body that makes insurance payments, the amount of these payments for citizens is preserved, and the amount of some - even increased. ATTENTION! A dormitory for 225 IDPs was repaired in Lviv Oblast In the dormitory of the Chervonohrad Mining and Economic College, 55 rooms for IDPs were renovated. The repairs were made within the framework of the Programme for the Implementation of Priority Infrastructure Projects in Lviv Oblast. For UAH 20 million, the roof was repaired, window blocks of the entire building were replaced, interior finishing works were carried out on three floors, door blocks and equipment were installed, water supply and sewage systems, electricity and heating were replaced, the entrance and hall were equipped. About 13 million hryvnias were allocated from the regional budget for this project, the rest is the funds of the Ma≈Çopolskie Voivodeship of the Republic of Poland and the local budget. Part of the equipment and furniture for the rooms was provided by World Vision International, Sean Penn's CORE, the public initiative "Let's Help Together", the UN Refugee Agency in Ukraine, EPAM, Polish Hotel Holding. Another part will be delivered soon. Photo: Maksym Kozytskyi

Kherson: SBU detains former head of "Russian railway branch", who helped to transfer Russian military echelons to Ukraine SBU exposed another enemy accomplice in the course of stabilization measures in liberated Kherson. The offender was a former official of an inter-sectoral railway transport enterprise, who joined the local occupation administration during the capture of the city. There she headed the "industrial railway transport enterprise "Kherson Railway" created by the aggressor. In this "position", she helped the enemy to establish a railway connection with the Ukrainian city to meet the needs of the occupation groups on the southern front. First of all, the criminal facilitated the transportation of military equipment, weapons and ammunition from the territory of Russia to the temporarily occupied part of Kherson region. She also organized the looting of technological equipment of rolling stock of the local enterprise of the Ukrainian railway for its transfer to the aggressor country. In addition, she personally urged local residents to support the Russian invaders and join the ranks of the occupation institution. For this, she promised a loyal attitude from the racists and the payment of "salaries" in Russian rubles. After leaving the regional center, the SBU officers detained the offender and served her a notice of suspicion under Part 1 Art. 111-2 (aiding the aggressor state) of the Criminal Code of Ukraine. The custody was chosen as a measure of restraint. The investigative and operative actions were conducted by officers of the SBU Main Directorate for Counterintelligence Support of Critical Infrastructure and Countering the Financing of Terrorism and the SBU Main Investigation Department under the procedural supervision of the Prosecutor General's Office.

Nanosatellite created to the 30th anniversary of Ukraine's Independence will be launched into Earth's orbit Today, on January 3, the Falcon-9 rocket of the SpaceX company will be launched into space in the United States, which will put satellites into orbit, one of which will be the Ukrainian nanosatellite PolyITAN-HP-30. It was created by specialists of the National Technical University of Ukraine "Igor Sikorsky Kyiv Polytechnic Institute" to the 30th anniversary of Independence of Ukraine. The satellite will help to conduct an experiment, the purpose of which is to investigate the effectiveness of the functioning of heat pipes of various designs as the main element of thermal stabilization systems of spacecraft. The launch will take place from Cape Canaveral. The launch vehicle is scheduled to take off at 16:56 Kyiv time. At 16:00 on the official YouTube channel of Igor Sikorsky Kyiv Polytechnic Institute a live broadcast of the satellite launching into orbit began.

Odesa region customs management exposed in embezzlement of hundreds of millions on grain exports - SBU More than 10 high-ranking officials embezzled millions of hryvnias from the export of Ukrainian grain. Among those involved are the deputy head of one of the departments of the State Customs Service and the management of Odesa Customs, who set up a mechanism for tax evasion for grain exports. Because of this, the state lost hundreds of millions of hryvnias. To implement the scheme, its participants involved more than 370 commercial structures with signs of fictitiousness through which they transferred products, the SBU reported. The suspects massively bought wheat from private farmers, agricultural enterprises and large agricultural holdings. It was established that this wheat was exported through the capacities of grain terminals in Odesa, Black Sea and Pivdennyi ports.

ü¶∫ How to wear flickers (reflective elements)? In order for pedestrians to be more visible in the dark and not to become victims of road accidents, the SES advises to wear reflective elements (flickers) on their clothes. The distance from which a driver notices a pedestrian in black clothes is 20 meters, in light clothes - 50 meters, and in clothes with reflective elements - 130 meters. While on dry asphalt, the braking distance of a car moving at a speed of 60 kilometers per hour exceeds 20 meters. Reflective elements can be in the form of bracelets, ribbons on the arm or backpack, stickers, key chains and vests. Retirement age in Ukraine will be individual: how to know when to retire In Ukraine, the requirements for retirement at the age of 60 will increase for another five years. As a result, in 2028, only those Ukrainians who have at least 35 years of experience will be able to receive payments on time. Every working person can already calculate their retirement age: ‚ñ™Ô∏èTo do this, as noted in the Pension Fund, you need to check your insurance record in the Pension Portal. Then calculate how much more experience you can earn before the age of 60. If you have enough experience, you can count on a pension. The Pension Fund also told how to check the seniority: In your personal account on the left, select the section "My insurance record", where you can view information about your insurance record and paid contributions. For retirement at the age of 60: ‚ñ´Ô∏è in 2023 - from 30 years; in 2024 - from the age of 31; in 2025 - from the age of 32; 2026 - from the age of 33; 2027 - from the age of 34; ‚ñ´Ô∏è in 2028 - from 35 years old. If you have not met this requirement, there is a chance to retire at the age of 63. To do this, you need to earn at least (depending on when you turn 63) by your 63rd birthday: ‚ñ´Ô∏èin 2022 - from 19 to 29 years; 2023 - from 20 to 30 years; In 2024 - from 21 to 31 years old; In 2025 - from 22 to 32 years old; In 2026 - from 23 to 33 years old; ‚ñ´Ô∏èin 2027 - from 24 to 34 years old. And starting next year, you must have at least 30 years of experience. Those who do not have enough experience will have to work until the age of 63 (if they have 23 years of experience) and 65 (if they have 15 to 23 years of experience). üêß Indian scientists have discovered that some species of wild penguins may have a certain degree of self-awareness. The researchers conducted four experiments. In the first, they simply put some mirrors on the ground near the penguins and watched as random penguins looked into them. The second involved building a cardboard pen around the penguins, which directed them to the mirrors. During the third, scientists placed small stickers in the shape of penguins on the mirrors. And during the last test, the researchers put bibs on the penguins and put them in front of the mirror. Scientists did not find the answer in the first experiment, which was actually a discovery: many animals do not pass such a test when they believe that the creature they see in the mirror is something else, and react accordingly. In the second experiment, the penguins moved in a way that suggested they were exploring themselves. The penguins were also worried looking at the mirrors with stickers and actively tried to remove them. But they did not react at all to the fact that they were wearing a small bib. @babel

In Turkey, a man accidentally discovered an ancient underground city during repairs - Metro News. Interestingly, the ancient settlement had temples, schools and stables for cattle. The Department of Culture of Turkey said that Derinkaya was carved in volcanic rock. Retirement age in Ukraine will be individual: how to know when to retire In Ukraine, the requirements for retirement at the age of 60 will increase for another five years. As a result, in 2028, only those Ukrainians who have at least 35 years of experience will be able to receive payments on time. Every working person can already calculate their retirement age: ‚ñ™Ô∏èTo do this, as noted in the Pension Fund, you need to check your insurance record in the Pension Portal. Then calculate how much more experience you can earn before the age of 60. If you have enough experience, you can count on a pension. The Pension Fund also told how to check the seniority: In your personal account on the left, select the section "My insurance record", where you can view information about your insurance record and paid contributions. For retirement at the age of 60: ‚ñ´Ô∏è in 2023 - from 30 years; in 2024 - from the age of 31; in 2025 - from the age of 32; 2026 - from the age of 33; 2027 - from the age of 34; ‚ñ´Ô∏è in 2028 - from 35 years old. If you have not met this requirement, there is a chance to retire at the age of 63. To do this, you need to earn at least (depending on when you turn 63) by your 63rd birthday: ‚ñ´Ô∏èin 2022 - from 19 to 29 years; 2023 - from 20 to 30 years; In 2024 - from 21 to 31 years old; In 2025 - from 22 to 32 years old; In 2026 - from 23 to 33 years old; ‚ñ´Ô∏èin 2027 - from 24 to 34 years old. And starting next year, you must have at least 30 years of experience. Those who do not have enough experience will have to work until the age of 63 (if they have 23 years of experience) and 65 (if they have 15 to 23 years of experience). üêß Indian scientists have discovered that some species of wild penguins may have a certain degree of self-awareness. The researchers conducted four experiments. In the first, they simply put some mirrors on the ground near the penguins and watched as random penguins looked into them. The second involved building a cardboard pen around the penguins, which directed them to the mirrors. During the third, scientists placed small stickers in the shape of penguins on the mirrors. And during the last test, the researchers put bibs on the penguins and put them in front of the mirror. Scientists did not find the answer in the first experiment, which was actually a discovery: many animals do not pass such a test when they believe that the creature they see in the mirror is something else, and react accordingly. In the second experiment, the penguins moved in a way that suggested they were exploring themselves. üè† How can IDPs join the queue for temporary housing? According to the Resolution of the Cabinet of Ministers, internally displaced persons can join the queue for temporary housing. Housing from the fund at the place of actual residence / stay within the territory of the authorized bodies is provided to IDPs and their family members free of charge and is determined in the amount of at least 6 square meters per person, Finance writes. üìù Citizens who were forced to move to other regions of Ukraine must submit an application for registration of persons in need of housing for temporary residence. The application is submitted to the authorized body within the territory of which they are registered in the Unified Information Database on IDPs. The application shall be accompanied by: ‚Üí copies of identity documents confirming the citizenship of Ukraine; ‚Üí copy of the internally displaced person's certificate of registration in the Unified Information Database on IDPs and copies of relevant certificates of family members (if any); ‚Üí copies of documents issued by the civil registry office or court confirming the kinship of the applicant and all members of his/her family (birth certificate, marriage certificate, certificate of guardian or custodian, etc;) ‚Üí copy of the registration number of the taxpayer's account card; ‚Üí copies of documents confirming the grounds for priority in providing IDPs with housing from the fund (the fact of destruction or damage to housing, which led to the impossibility of its intended use, is confirmed by a personal statement of the applicant and his family members). After submitting the application, a decision is made within one working day to register IDPs as citizens in need of housing for temporary residence or to refuse to register them.

What will be the prices for apartments in Kyiv in 2023: expert forecast In 2022, real estate prices in Kyiv decreased by about 15-20%, but in 2023 the cost will not fall. Prices are likely to remain at the current level for the next six months. However, the situation will be influenced by the news from the front. This was told by the President of the Association of Realtors of Ukraine Yuriy Pita. According to him, there is a demand for apartments in the capital, but many people are still in no hurry to buy real estate, as the risks due to the war still remain. "We will rely on the trends of the last few months - November-December - because the market has basically stabilized. There are no significant shifts in the direction of increase or decrease in value. In 2022, prices fell by about 15-20%, this is since the beginning of the war. They are not continuing their fall, so prices will be at this level. They have fallen to a certain level and will remain so. But, again, much will depend on the situation in the country as a whole," the expert explained. Pita added: if there are successes on the front, then the real estate market will also react quite actively. In addition, compensation to Ukrainians who lost their homes will have a positive impact on the situation. "We hope that housing compensation programs will be launched for those who have lost their homes. This will also affect the market. There will be, perhaps, some monetary compensation or square meters. And the apartments on the market will be searched for somewhere, bought, transferred to those who suffered. So, such trends will be at least six months, and then we will see what will happen next.
